<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900924-0121</DOCNO><DOCID>900924-0121.</DOCID><HL>   RJR Nabisco Agrees to Sell   More Cigarettes to Soviets</HL><DATE>09/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   RJR FREST</CO><IN>TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><LP>   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. -- RJR Nabisco Inc., which already hasplans to ship 14 billion cigarettes to the Soviet Union, saidit agreed to ship an additional 3.2 billion smokes.   The food and tobacco company, controlled by KohlbergKravis Roberts andamp; Co., also said it agreed in principle toexpanded long-term cooperation with the Soviet tobaccoindustry. The agreement includes technical assistance toimprove manufacturing facilities throughout the Soviet Union.</LP><TEXT>   Analysts estimated RJR's original plan to provide 14billion cigarettes to the Soviets would generate about $40million in operating profit. In 1989, RJR's operating profitfrom tobacco exports totaled $328 million. The companydeclined to comment on the original estimate, or to projectwhat the added tobacco shipments might contribute toearnings.   RJR said the first air-freight shipments of cigarettes areexpected to begin this week, with cigarettes arriving onSoviet shelves before the end of the month. Shipments of thetotal 17.2 billion cigarettes, the company said, willcontinue over the next 12 months.</TEXT></DOC>